04012nam a22004455i 9780226817477DE-B159720220830111616.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220830t20222022ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226817477  a(DE-B1597)627840  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aN6494 7aART0000002bisacsh04a709.04/071 aBruno, Giuliana, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAtmospheres of Projection :bEnvironmentality in Art and Screen Media /cGiuliana Bruno. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (368 p.) :b91 color plates, 31 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tProjection and Atmosphere: An Introduction, in Medias Res -- tThe Cultural Atmosphere of Projection -- t1 The Ambiance of Projection: An Environmental Archaeology of Mediality -- t2 Sites of Transmission: Psychic Transformation and Relationality -- t3 Atmospheres of Transduction: Relatedness and Sympathy -- tEnvironmentality: The Art of Projection -- t4 Projective Climates in Art: The Screen as Environmental Medium -- t5 Alchemic Milieus: Diana Thater’s Phantasmagoric Habitats -- t6 The Nature of Scale: Jesper Just’s Mareoramic Environments -- t7 The Thickness of Projection: Cristina Iglesias’s Weathered Screen Casts -- t8 Elemental Empathy: Chantal Akerman’s Psychic Atmospheres -- t9 Atmospheric Screening: Rosa Barba and Performative Projection -- t10 Fluid Ecology: Giorgio Andreotta Calò and Liquid Screens -- t11 Environmental Projection: Robert Irwin and Nebular Atmospheres -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBringing together cultural history, visual studies, and media archaeology, Bruno considers the interrelations of projection, atmosphere, and environment. Projection has long been transforming space, from shadow plays to camera obscuras and magic lantern shows. Our fascination with projection is alive on the walls of museums and galleries and woven into our daily lives. Giuliana Bruno explores the histories of projection and atmosphere in visual culture and their continued importance to contemporary artists who are reinventing the projective imagination with atmospheric thinking and the use of elemental media. To explain our fascination with projection and atmosphere, Bruno traverses psychoanalysis, environmental philosophy, architecture, the history of science, visual art, and moving image culture to see how projective mechanisms and their environments have developed over time. She reveals how atmosphere is formed and mediated, how it can change, and what projection can do to modify a site. In so doing, she gives new life to the alchemic possibilities of transformative projective atmospheres. Showing how their “environmentality” produces sites of exchange and relationality, this book binds art to the ecology of atmosphere.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 7aART / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076650940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226817477423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226817477/original  a978-3-11-076650-9  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles